The US Supreme Court is deliberating on the case of Christopher Simmons, who was sentenced to death at 17 for a brutal murder.
There is a global push to end the execution of minors, with concerns about evolving standards of decency.
Advocates argue that executing juvenile offenders is as wrong as executing the mentally challenged.
The court is grappling with the morality of executing individuals who committed crimes as minors.
The case has drawn attention to the issue of capital punishment for young offenders, with calls for a minimum age of 18 for such sentences.
The justices are also considering other cases related to criminal justice, including medical marijuana and the detention of Cuban criminals.
